\f2\b Basic Shell Commands
\f1\b0 \

\f2\b cd
\f1\b0     change directory\

\f2\b cd ~
\f1\b0    change to your main home directory\

\f2\b cd ~/Documents/
\f1\b0   change into your home documents directory\

\f2\b cd ../
\f1\b0    the \'91../\'92 goes back a directory from the current location\
\

\f2\b ls
\f1\b0   list contents of current directory\

\f2\b ls -al
\f1\b0   a command followed by a \'91-\'92 and one ore more letters accesses optional abilities of the command. In this case, this will list contents of the directory, including hidden files and additional info.\
\

\f2\b mkdir
\f1\b0    make new directory. Follow mkdir with the name you want for the directory (ex: mkdir mynewfolder)\
\

\f2\b touch
\f1\b0    create new file. follow touch with the name of the new file (ex: touch index.html)\
\

\f2\b rm
\f1\b0    remove file or directory. Follow the command with a \'91r\'92 flag to remove directories and all files within. This is immediate and irreversible so make sure you check  before running! (ex: rm myfile, rm -r myfolder) \
\

\f2\b cp
\f1\b0   copy file. cp /path/to/filetocopy  /path/to/new/location/newfilename\
\

\f2\b mv
\f1\b0   move file. mv /path/to/filetocopy  /path/to/new/location/newfilename\
\

\f2\b apt install
\f1\b0   on Ubuntu Linux, use the apt install to install new software from the Ubuntu repository. (ex: apt install frozen-bubble will install the game Frozen Bubble on your machine)\
\

\f2\b apt remove
\f1\b0   if you no longer want a particular piece of software, use the apt remove command. (ex: apt remove frozen-bubble will remove the game)\
\

\f2\b sudo
\f1\b0   sudo is used when you need to do something that requires admin privileges. This often comes up when installing or removing, so oftentimes you weill need to enter: sudo apt install <application>. Using sudo requires you to know an administrator password. On these laptops, the admininstrator name and password is \'91
